'''Group medical practices''' practice medicine by physicians who share resources.<ref>[http://www.thefreedictionary.com Online Dictionary, Encyclopedia and Thesaurus. Free access<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
There are approximately 230,187 physician practices in the [[United States]].<ref>Market research study done by [http://www.skainfo.com SK&A]</ref> Among the physician practices, 16.5% had only one office-based physician in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kane|first1=Carol K.|title=Policy Research Perspectives|url=https://www.ama-assn.org/sites/default/files/media-browser/public/health-policy/PRP-2016-physician-benchmark-survey.pdf|website=www.ama-assn.org|publisher=The American Medical Association|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> Physician group practices with 2-4 physicians make up 22.3% of physician offices in the United States, 19.8% have 5-10 physicians, 12.1% have 11-24 physicians, 6.3% have 25-49, and the remaining 13.5% have 50 or more physicians.
In recent years, many small or solo practitioners have come together to form larger specialty groups because of [[managed care]].<ref>Schick David (November 29, 2011)Is Coming Together to Form the Larger Same (or Multi) Specialty Medical Practice the Answer? [http://www.natlawreview.com/article/coming-together-to-form-larger-same-or-multi-specialty-medical-practice-answer] The [[National Law Review]] </ref>
== Formal definition == The [[Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services]] (CMS) changed the definition of "group practice" in its 2012 physician fee schedule to mean 25 or more eligible professionals in the same practice.<ref>{{cite web|title=MGMA Meaningful Use Stage 2 proposed rule comments|url=http://www.mgma.com/WorkArea/mgma_downloadasset.aspx?id=1370783&ei=TZ9sUL2AL6nfyAGl-IGQBQ&usg=AFQjCNH1NnkkVB2jmzjikp7hojvxStiuKA}}</ref>
