In [[sociology]], '''trained incapacity''' is "that state of affairs in which one's abilities function as inadequacies or blind spots."<ref name="Merton1968">{{cite book|author=Robert King Merton|title=Handschift und charakter: gemeinverstandlicher abriss der graphologischen technik|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dyqZOcux9o0C&pg=PA252|accessdate=28 March 2013|year=1968|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-02-921130-4|page=252}}</ref>  It means that people's past experiences can lead to wrong decisions when circumstances change.<ref name="Merz2011">{{cite book|author=Felix Merz|title=Max Weber ́s Theory of Bureaucracy and Its Negative Consequences|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ulFb1oRXTIC&pg=PA16|accessdate=28 March 2013|date=23 July 2011|publisher=GRIN Verlag|isbn=978-3-640-96563-2|page=16}}</ref><ref name="Shepard2009">{{cite book|author=Jon M. Shepard|title=Sociology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FzefFQ-WMlYC&pg=PA158|accessdate=28 March 2013|date=9 January 2009|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-495-59901-2|page=158}}</ref>  [[Thorstein Veblen]] invented the concept in 1933.<ref name="Burke1984">{{cite book|author=Kenneth Burke|title=Permanence and Change: An Anatomy of Purpose|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E4_BU8v2TPUC&pg=PA7|accessdate=28 March 2013|year=1984|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04146-2|page=7}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Wais|first=Erin|title=Trained Incapacity: Thorstein Veblen and Kenneth Burke|journal=K. B. Journal|date=Fall 2005|volume=2|issue=1|url=http://www.kbjournal.org/wais|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

